INSERT INTO materials (course_id, title, type, link, pages, content_text) VALUES

-- 1. Chapter 3 - Agile Software Development
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'Chapter 3 - Agile Software Development',
'slides',
'/materials/sen201/Ch_3_Agile_Software_Development.pdf',
35,
'Chapter 3 – Agile Software Development. Topics covered: Agile methods, Agile development techniques, Agile project management. The Problem(s) with Software Development: Customers do not know exactly what they need or want, Customers change their minds, Customers priorities change, It is difficult to solve the needs of many stakeholders, We can never adequately specify requirements, We are lousy at estimating software tasks, Unpredictable stuff happens, It often takes several times to get something right. Users do not know what they want until they see it. Agile Manifesto: We are uncovering better ways of developing software by doing it and helping others do it. Through this work we have come to value: Individuals and interactions over processes and tools, Working software over comprehensive documentation, Customer collaboration over contract negotiation, Responding to change over following a plan. Principles behind the Manifesto: 1. Our highest priority is to satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software. 2. Welcome changing requirements, even late in development. 3. Deliver working software frequently. 4. Business people and developers must work together daily. 5. Build projects around motivated individuals. 6. Face-to-face conversation is most efficient. 7. Working software is the primary measure of progress. 8. Agile processes promote sustainable development. 9. Continuous attention to technical excellence. 10. Simplicity is essential. 11. Best architectures emerge from self-organizing teams. 12. Team reflects on how to become more effective. Key Aspects of Agile: Iterative (planned modification of parts), Incremental (develop parts separately and integrate), Self-Organizing (team organizes internal dynamics), Emergent (tools and requirements emerge in process). Principles of agile methods: Customer involvement, Incremental delivery, People not process, Embrace change, Maintain simplicity. Waterfall vs Agile: Waterfall has detailed plan, sequential phases, errors magnified, functionality at end, project manager, requirements analysis, reports. Agile has dynamic plan, iterative phases, errors minimized, functionality after each iteration, team self management, customers working with team, communication. Agile Implementations: Extreme Programming, Scrum, Iterative development, Kanban. Theme, Epic, Story, Task hierarchy. User Stories: describe how system should behave from user viewpoint. INVEST criteria: Independent, Negotiable, Valuable, Estimatable, Small, Testable. Story Walls display status of cards. Epic is a big story too big for single sprint. Scrum: Product Owner decides what to build, Scrum Master facilitates, Development Team builds. Sprint Planning, Daily Standup, Sprint Review, Sprint Retrospective. Extreme Programming (XP): values simplicity, communication, feedback, courage. Practices include pair programming, test-first development, refactoring, continuous integration, small releases. Kanban: visualize workflow, limit work in progress, manage flow, make policies explicit, improve collaboratively.'),

-- 2. Lecture 2 - Software Process Models & SDLC
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'Lecture 2 - Software Process Models & SDLC',
'slides',
'/materials/sen201/Lecture_2_Software_Process_Models.pptx',
40,
'SEN 201: Introduction to Software Engineering - Lecture 2. The Software Process: A structured set of activities required to develop a software system. Many different software processes but all involve: Specification (defining what system should do), Design and implementation (defining organization and implementing), Validation (checking it does what customer wants), Evolution (changing system in response to changing needs). A software process model is an abstract representation of a process. Software Process Descriptions: Process descriptions may include Products (outcomes), Roles (responsibilities), Pre- and post-conditions. Modern Approach to Systems Analysis and Design: 1950s focus on efficient automation, 1960s advent of 3GL, 1970s engineering discipline, 1980s 4GL CASE tools object oriented methods, 1990s system integration GUI client/server Internet, New century Web applications wireless PDAs component-based development. Application Software: software designed to support technical collaborative and managerial activities. Systems Analyst: organizational role most responsible for analysis and design. Plan-driven processes: all activities planned in advance. Agile processes: planning is incremental. Process Activities: Real software processes are inter-leaved sequences of technical collaborative and managerial activities. Systems Development Life Cycle (SDLC): Traditional methodology to develop maintain and replace information systems. Phases: Planning, Analysis, Design, Implementation, Maintenance. Software Process Models: The Waterfall Model (plan-driven, separate phases), Incremental Development (specification development validation interleaved), Integration and Configuration (assembled from existing components). SDLC phases detailed: Planning (needs identified analyzed prioritized), Analysis (requirements studied and structured), Design (solution converted to logical then physical specifications), Logical design (functional features described independently of platform), Physical design (logical specs transformed to technology-specific details), Implementation (system coded tested installed supported), Maintenance (system systematically repaired and improved). Heart of development: analysis-design-code-test loop. Traditional Waterfall SDLC vs iterative approaches. Software Specification: establishes what services required and constraints. Requirements Engineering: feasibility study, requirements elicitation and analysis, requirements specification, requirements validation. Software Design and Implementation: converting specification into executable system. Design activities: architectural design, database design, interface design, component selection and design. Software Validation: verification and validation (V&V). Testing stages: component testing, system testing, customer testing. Software Evolution: software is inherently flexible and can change. Coping with Change: change is inevitable. System prototyping: experimental version for requirements exploration. Incremental delivery: increments delivered to customer for use and experimentation. Process Improvement: understanding existing processes and changing to improve quality, reduce costs, or accelerate schedules. Process maturity approach and agile approach.'),

-- 3. Software Prototyping Techniques (Student Project)
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'Software Prototyping Techniques - Case Study Project',
'slides',
'/materials/sen201/Software_Prototyping_Techniques_Project.pptx',
14,
'SEN 201 - Software Prototyping Techniques. Case study: Development of a Mobile Application for Local Event Discovery (Lagos Events App). Overview: Lagos events app addresses discovering and participating in local events such as cultural festivals, business networking meetups, concerts, workshops, and community gatherings. Currently event information is scattered across social media, websites, and word-of-mouth. Target Function: aggregate events from various sources (APIs from event platforms, user submissions, partnerships with local organizers), allow users to search by location category date or price, view details, register/RSVP, receive notifications. Feasible using cross-platform frameworks like Flutter or React Native with backend support from Firebase or AWS. Prototype Implementation Summary: adopts prototyping-based methodology combining throw-away and low-fidelity prototype. Emphasizes early feedback, risk reduction, and iterative refinement. Prototyping Technique Applied: Throwaway and low-fidelity prototyping. Why? Quick to create, low cost, focuses on layout and flow, gathers early feedback. Step-by-step process: 1. Define basic requirements 2. Create simple wireframes (screens and user flow) 3. Show to potential users for feedback 4. Refine layout and features. Throw away prototype main user flow includes: search, home, tickets, RSVP, profile screens. Low-Fidelity Prototypes help users feel how the actual software will look. Wireframes created quickly to visualize ideas and get user feedback on navigation and layout before coding.'),

-- 4. Waterfall Method Planning
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'The Waterfall Method - Project Management & Planning',
'slides',
'/materials/sen201/Waterfall_Method_Planning.pptx',
17,
'The Proper Way to Plan - The Waterfall Method. Project Management and Leadership. What does it mean to plan? Planning is laying out what you are going to do before you do it. It is very helpful with big important tasks but helps a lot with small ones too. Everyone uses planning - friends, family. Why is planning so important? Planning things out saves so much time. If you try to do everything without planning you will run into problems. The Waterfall Method: A type of planning used for simple tasks. It got its name because it has steps that flow down like a waterfall. Example: Going to school in the morning - Step 1: Wake up, Step 2: Get dressed, Step 3: Eat breakfast, Step 4: Get on the bus. In this order you can easily see which step is first. You cannot get dressed without waking up first. Waterfall Planning Activity: planning a birthday party. Steps must be in correct order: 1. Decide who will be invited 2. Decide the party theme 3. Decide where the party will be and schedule it 4. Invite your friends 5. Figure out the food/drinks 6. Decide what cake you want 7. Order the cake. The order matters because planning helps organize tasks so you do not make mistakes. What did we learn: Planning makes complicated tasks easier, Everyone uses it, Planning keeps you organized.'),

-- 5. Prototyping Evening Class Lecture
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'Prototyping - Comprehensive Lecture',
'slides',
'/materials/sen201/Prototyping_Evening_Class.ppt',
25,
'Prototyping Lecture. Agenda: Define Prototyping, Need/Importance for prototyping, Types of prototypes, Prototyping as methodology, User interface prototyping, Advantages and disadvantages, Lessons learnt. Prototyping Defined: The process of quickly putting together a working model (prototype) to test various aspects of a design, illustrate ideas or features and gather early user feedback. IEEE defines prototyping as a type of development in which emphasis is placed on developing prototypes early in the development process to permit early feedback and analysis. Need for prototyping: Enables exploration of problem space with stakeholders, As requirements artifact to initially envision the system, As design artifact to explore solution space, Vehicle to communicate possible UI designs, Potential foundation to continue developing system. Advantages of Prototyping: Users can try system and provide constructive feedback during development, Operational prototype can be produced in weeks, Users become more positive about implementing as they see solution emerging, Enables early detection of errors. Disadvantages: Each iteration builds on previous making it difficult to reject initial solution, Formal end-of-phase reviews do not occur making it difficult to contain scope, System documentation often absent or incomplete, Backup recovery performance and security issues can be overlooked. Types of prototyping: Throw-away Prototyping (developed from initial requirements but not used for final project, some developers believe waste of time, must use easy to use language), Evolutionary Prototyping (most fundamental form, main concept to build robust prototype and constantly improve it, objective to deliver working system, straddles ground between evolutionary prototyping and staged delivery), Low Fidelity Prototyping (limited function limited interaction, constructed to depict concepts design alternatives and screen layouts, intended to demonstrate general look and feel, used early in design cycle), High Fidelity Prototyping (represent core functionality of user interface, fully interactive systems where users can enter data respond to messages select icons, trade-off speed for accuracy, consume resources and have high cost). Evolutionary Prototyping phases include continuous improvement. Advantages of evolutionary: always looking for new ways to improve, increases chance of client satisfaction, can be used when requirements not defined, quicker delivery. Disadvantages of evolutionary: can avoid documenting requirements, long term maintenance expensive, uncertain design ideas, information lost through many changes, management required. Prototyping as methodology: The Throwaway Prototyping Model starts with requirements analysis then quick design then build prototype then user evaluates prototype then refine requirements and repeat or proceed to final system. User Interface Prototyping is important because it is difficult to do a priori UI design, best approach is to develop prototypes of the UI and test with end users. Benefits of UI prototyping: helps with analysis of requirements, particularly user requirements. Issues: should not be part of production system, throw prototype away after development.'),

-- 6. SEN201 Assignment - Waterfall Model Applications
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'SEN201 Assignment - Waterfall Model Real-World Applications',
'notes',
'/materials/sen201/SEN201_Assignment_Waterfall_Applications.pdf',
4,
'SEN201 Assignment: Waterfall Model Applications. 1. Using the Waterfall Model to Implement an Electronic Health Record (EHR) System (ensuring regulatory compliance): EHR handles sensitive patient information, mistakes lead to privacy breaches wrong treatment lawsuits. Waterfall works well because it emphasizes clear requirements strong documentation strict testing. Phases: a. Requirements Gathering and Analysis (hospital and developers agree on what system must do, regulatory requirements captured, SRS document produced), b. System Design (prevents building wrong structure, design documents used during audits), c. Implementation/Coding (developers build module by module according to approved design - patients lab pharmacy billing reporting), d. Testing and Verification (done with requirements document as reference to prove compliance), e. Deployment and Maintenance (bug fixes, updates for new guidelines, performance improvement). Why Waterfall fits: Regulatory environments prefer strong documentation and traceability, Hospitals need stability, Supports formal approval and sign-off. 2. Using Waterfall to Design an Aerospace System: Safety-critical systems where small error can lead to loss of lives. Phases: a. Requirements Analysis (performance limits safety constraints reliability targets, standards and certification, environmental conditions, risk analysis), b. Design (redundancy fault tolerance detailed interface definitions documented design reviews), c. Implementation (follows design strictly using standards for safety-critical software), d. Testing and Validation (unit testing integration testing simulation testing verification and validation stress and reliability testing), e. Deployment and Maintenance (controlled changes follow strict approval procedures). Why Waterfall works: Requirements usually stable and regulated, Certification requires documentation, Safety-critical systems need step-by-step validation. Limitation: Late requirement changes are expensive. 3. How a Financial Institution Can Use Waterfall for Online Banking Platform: Banking handles money identity confidential data, must be secure accurate compliant. Phases: a. Requirements Analysis (account management transfers bill payments, login OTP/2FA session control, compliance rules KYC AML transaction limits audit requirements, non-functional needs security speed availability scalability), b. System Design (secure architecture APIs database authentication, encryption access control fraud detection, transaction processing design, monitoring and logging), c. Implementation (user onboarding registration, payments transfers, transaction verification notifications), d. Testing (functional testing correct balances transfers, security testing penetration vulnerability scanning, performance testing, compliance checks audit logging verification), e. Deployment and Maintenance (monitors with patches and regulated updates). Why suitable: Banks prefer predictable planning and clear documentation, Errors have direct financial consequences, Auditing easier with documentation. Limitation: User expectations change fast in fintech. Conclusion: Waterfall most suitable when requirements are stable and system must meet strict standards - EHR (healthcare compliance) aerospace (safety-critical certification) banking (security and regulatory requirements).'),

-- 7. What is Prototyping in Software Development and Why It is Important
('441840da-c695-44cb-8810-d5265ddf7b9e',
'What is Prototyping in Software Development and Why It is Important',
'notes',
'/materials/sen201/Prototyping_in_Software_Development_Importance.pdf',
11,
'What is Prototyping in Software Development and Why It is Important. What is a Software Prototype? A prototype in software development is a simulation of how a real software product will look work and feel. Typically built early in the software development process, prototypes are primarily for design feedback and user testing. Software prototypes can come in all levels of sophistication from an idea sketched on the back of a napkin to a clickable prototype that mimics real software. A prototype can simulate an entire mobile app or just one digital interaction. Think of prototypes like scale building models used in architectural design. It is easier and cheaper to make changes based on an early prototype instead of waiting until finishing touches are made. Why Prototyping is Important: prototyping is the ideal way to test evaluate and validate your idea with users and the internal team. It lets you confirm that you are building the RIGHT product and features before you actually code anything. Prototyping reduces project risk. You do not want to find out AFTER months of costly developer time that features do not meet user needs. As IDEO says: If a picture is worth a thousand words then a prototype is worth a thousand meetings. Different Types of Software Prototyping: 1. Handmade Drawings (Paper Wireframes) - sketch idea on paper, forces you to move to the concrete, extremely easy to change and test different ideas. 2. Wireframes (Low Fidelity Design) - digital wireframes are 2D skeletal outlines, represent initial concept of product, focus on functionality user flow and how screens relate, minimal styling color and graphics, great communication tools for eliciting feedback, their rough feel encourages honest comments. 3. Clickable Prototypes (High Fidelity Design) - interactive set of linked visual screens that mimic a working app, users can interact on computer or mobile device, click buttons and move fluidly, no actual coding has taken place, clear sense of what final software will look and feel like. Why Start a Product with a Software Prototype: 1. Test Validate and Iterate on Designs Early, 2. Impress Investors or Early Adopters, 3. Adaptive to Your Needs. Creating a Software Prototype process: 1. Understanding Software Requirements (deep dive into client requirements and vision, UX/UI designers extract detailed information about features functionality user experience goals, create detailed map of user workflows), 2. Initial Conceptualization (wireframing and low-fidelity prototyping using specialized software, focus on layout structure and basic interactions), 3. Feedback Gathering and Iteration (present low-fidelity prototype to client, iterate on design functionality and user experience), 4. High-Fidelity Prototyping (adding detailed visual elements branding and interactive components), 5. User Testing and Feedback (subjected to user testing to identify usability issues), 6. Refinement and Final Approval (refine based on user feedback, present for final approval). Advantage of iterative process: full confidence in product you are building and spending resources on right functionality and design.');
